 <div class="col-md-8">
	<h3>Current or past students.</h3>
		<ul>
          <li><b>2025-2026:</b> <i>Eric S</i> <!-- <a href="#">(personnal website)</a> </br> --> 
          is performing a REU with <a href="https://www.beloit.edu/live/profiles/3214-ben-stucky">Ben Stucky</a> 
          since May 2025<br> 
          to work on an open question which emerged from our joint work 
          about <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.16216">The pinning ideal of a multiloop</a>. <br>
          This ongoing work will lead to a prepublication: 
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.16216">The complexity of pinning simple multiloops</a> <br>
          showing that the problem of pinning simple multiloops is in P for <4 strands but NP-C for >17 strands.
          </li>
          
          <li><b>2024-2025:</b> <i>Ryan Pham</i> <!-- <a href="#">(personnal website)</a> </br> -->
          performed a REU with <a href="https://www.beloit.edu/live/profiles/3214-ben-stucky">Ben Stucky</a> 
          from September 2024 and to May 2025<br>          
          to implement the Shor-Van-Wick algorithm which we use 
          to compute a boolean formula for the pinning ideal of a loop.<br>
          In particular this algorithm is now used to enhance the data basis 
          <a href="https://christopherlloyd.github.io/LooPindex/">his github project</a>
          and this work was <a href="https://www.beloit.edu/live/news/7240-computer-science-major-presents-advanced-research">advertised here</a>.
          </li>
          
          <li><b>2023-2024:</b> <i>Mayank Yadav</i> performed a REU with me from January 2023 to May 2024<br> 
          <!-- <a href="#">(personnal website)</a> </br> -->
          to investigate chord diagrams of loops and their interlace graphs. <br>
          In particular his experimental results are available at 
          <a href="https://github.com/mayankyadavblr">his github project</a>. <br>
          This ongoing work will lead to a prepublication about <br>
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.08806">Vertex complements of graphs: split-decomposition and interlace polynomials</a>.
          </li>
          
		</ul>
	
